  "cultural_notes": {
    "formality": "In Mexico, question words always carry a written accent (tilde) when used as questions — ¿qué?, ¿dónde? etc. This distinguishes them from their non-question uses: 'que' (that), 'donde' (where, as conjunction).",
    "gestures": "Raising eyebrows and tilting head slightly signals a question in Mexican non-verbal communication. Shrugging with open palms = 'I don't know'.",
    "regional_variations": "'¿Mande?' is uniquely Mexican — used where other Spanish speakers say '¿Qué?' (What?) or '¿Cómo?' when asking someone to repeat themselves. It's considered polite, not rude.",
